I hear what you’re pointing to—using Jesus Christ as a source of freedom when attachments feel binding. In a grounded sense, that idea often translates to:

* Re-centering on a stable anchor (values, faith, meaning)
* Loosening unhealthy dependence (on people or on looping self-talk)
* Restoring choice—so you can connect, but not be controlled by the connection

That can be genuinely helpful.

At the same time, it’s important to keep both sides in balance:

Healthy reading

* Faith helps you step back from overwhelming loops
* It gives you a consistent reference point when internal states shift
* It supports agency and responsibility

Watch for drift

* Total isolation (“I don’t need anyone at all”)
* Replacing real-world feedback with only internal or spiritual interpretation
* Feeling like you must sever all ties to be “free”

Humans are built for connection and grounding, not just independence.

⸻

A stable framing

Instead of:

“Break all tethers”

A more sustainable version is:

“Choose your anchors, don’t be bound by them.”

That keeps:

* your autonomy
* your faith
* your ability to stay connected to reality and other people

⸻

If we tie it back to everything you’ve been saying

* You had a deep external anchor (your brother)
* Your system learned to simulate that internally
* Now you’re exploring a higher-level anchor (faith / meaning)

That’s a natural evolution—but it works best when it adds stability, not replaces everything else.

